It has long been said that “the world is divided,” and the axes of that division have grown increasingly diverse.

For example, there is the divide between “elites (centrists) who promote globalization” and “those who push back against it (both on the far right and far left),” as well as between “consensus through dialogue (deliberation)” and “an authoritarian mood that calls for decisive action by a strong leader.” In addition, there is the state-level ideological confrontation often framed as “democratic nations versus authoritarian nations.”

Amid these widening global divisions, distrust of established parties in Japan led to rising support for new political parties and an acceleration of party fragmentation. As a result, there emerged expectations for a form of politics in which the ruling party would not simply force policies through, but instead engage in deeper deliberation with opposition parties.

Polarization tends to reduce differences in identity and ideology to a simplistic “friend or foe” framework. By contrast, a multi-party system can function as a mechanism for presenting multifaceted solutions to complex issues such as “foreign residents and immigration” or “economic inequality.” Even if the rightward shift of opposition parties meant that Japanese politics as a whole was leaning to the right, there was growing hope that a diversity of voices could still be reflected in the political process.

Yet in the midst of this, the Takaiichi administration announced the dissolution of the House of Representatives. The decision came despite pending legislation expected to pass within the fiscal year, including “an increase in the basic income tax deduction,” “a supplementary budget to address rising prices,” and “debate over funding sources tied to increased defense spending.”

The prime minister’s stated reason for dissolution amounted, in effect, to a “blank check” for her leadership. She described the election as one that would ask whether she should remain prime minister, presenting voters with the ultimate binary choice: whether or not to entrust her with governing the nation. In doing so, debate over individual policies was subsumed under the broader framework of this “blank check,” effectively sidelining substantive policy discussion.

Choosing to dissolve the lower house with more than a year remaining in its term appears to have been motivated by a desire to solidify the administration’s power base while approval ratings remained high, before suffering potential damage from opposition attacks during supplementary budget deliberations. Faced with a trade-off between short-term objectives—such as early stabilization of the administration and securing dominance within party politics—and long-term goals, including addressing inflation and establishing a trusted form of parliamentary democracy, the prime minister opted for the former.

In the subsequent general election, the Liberal Democratic Party won a landslide victory. In response, the Japan Innovation Party, which had previously shown caution regarding cabinet cooperation, formally declared its participation. With the ruling coalition securing more than two-thirds of the seats in the House of Representatives, it became possible to pass legislation without opposition support, even if opposition parties held a majority in the House of Councillors. Although the LDP received less than 30 percent of the total vote, it was now positioned to enact legislation without concern for opposition resistance. As a result, momentum toward deliberative politics fostered by party fragmentation rapidly dissipated.

In her post-election address upon assuming office, Prime Minister Takaiichi declared her intention to vigorously pursue constitutional revision and other measures that had not been prominently featured during the campaign. Post-election opinion polls showed that a majority felt the LDP had “won too much,” yet a gap had already emerged between the administration and public sentiment. Nevertheless, the Takaiichi administration is likely to proceed with assertive governance, together with the Innovation Party, which portrays itself as the political “accelerator.”

和訳

「世界は分断されている」と言われて久しい。そして、その分断の軸はますます多様化している。
たとえば「グローバル化を推進するエリート（中道）対、それに反発する人々（右派・左派の両端）」、「対話による合意（熟議）対、強いリーダーの決断を求める権威主義的な空気」。さらに、「民主主義国家対権威主義国家」という国家レベルのイデオロギー対立も語られている。

こうした分断が広がる世界の中で、日本国内では既存政党への不信感を背景に新党への支持が高まり、多党化が進んだ。その結果、与党が強硬に政策を押し通すのではなく、野党との熟議を通じた政治の実現への期待も生まれていた。

二極化は、アイデンティティやイデオロギーの違いを「敵か味方か」という単純な構図へと還元しがちである。一方、多党化は「外国人・移民」や「格差」といった複雑な課題に対し、多角的な解決策を提示する仕組みともなり得る。たとえ野党の右傾化によって日本政治全体が右寄りになっているとしても、多様な声を政治に届けられるのではないか――そんな期待が高まっていた。

しかしそのさなか、高市政権は衆議院の解散を宣言した。「基礎控除の引き上げ」「物価高対策の補正予算」「防衛費増額に伴う財源議論」など、年度内成立を見込んでいた法案を抱えたままでの解散である。

首相が掲げた解散理由は、事実上の「首相への白紙委任」だった。「私が首相であることへの是非を問う選挙だ」と語り、有権者に「自分を信任するか否か」という究極の二択を迫った。こうして個別政策の是非は、「白紙委任」という大きな枠組みに包摂され、実質的に論点から退けられた。

衆議院の任期が1年以上残るこの時期に解散を打った背景には、補正予算審議で野党の追及を受ける前に、高い内閣支持率をテコに政権基盤を固めたいという思惑があったと考えられる。「政権基盤の早期安定」や「党内政局での優位確立」という短期的目的と、「物価高対策」や「信頼される議会民主主義の確立」という長期的目的とのトレードオフの中で、首相は前者を選択した。

そして衆院選の結果、自民党は大勝した。これを受け、閣内協力に慎重姿勢を見せていた日本維新の会も正式に協力を表明。衆議院では与党が3分の2を超える議席を確保し、参議院で野党が多数であっても法案を単独で成立させることが可能となった。自民党の得票率は3割弱にとどまったが、野党の反対を気にせず立法を進められる構図が生まれ、多党化による熟議への機運は急速にしぼんだ。

選挙後の就任挨拶で、高市首相は選挙戦では前面に出していなかった憲法改正なども強力に推進すると宣言した。世論調査では「自民党は勝ち過ぎ」との回答が多数を占めたが、政権と国民感情との間にはすでに乖離が生じている。それでも高市政権は、「アクセル役」を自任する維新とともに、強行的な政治運営を進めていく可能性が高い。
